Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: I'm pretty surprised to see all the 5 star reviews of this special, because for me, it was ok. Louis CK is an extremely funny dude, but I felt this material was a bit raw. It's like he had the outline for a good show, solid topics and all, but then just went on stage and was winging it. The setups were there, but when it came time for the punchline, it just didn't pop. An example from the beginning of the show was the Hitler vs Ray Charles comparison. That had SO much potential, and it was kind of funny, but he could have done more with it. Some jokes had my dying, but most of the special seemed to drag. An hour and 24 mins is a LONG special too, so that could be part of the problem. That's a ton of time to fill. I'd much rather a comedian do a shorter set and have me rolling the whole time, than give me an hour plus of OK material.If you already like Louis CK, its worth checkin out, but don't expect to be blown away. If you are knew to him, start with "Shameless" - that special is top-notch.
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: Louis CK's standup act is considerably raunchier than his tv show.  You will like this show.  It is impossible not to like it but if you love his tv show, as I do, it lacks the more subtle comic stylings of his tv show.  This is much broader humor.  Also, where Louis CK is strongest to me is in his observations about human nature, his daughter, his dating, his friends and so forth.  He is less funny to me when he gets going about the more obvious raunch that is familiar to stand up audiences.  I actually like him better than George Carlin though, who was the undisputed king of what Louis CK does in his standup act. So if you are looking for a replacement for the late Carlin, you've found him.This show is called hilarious because he really resents how the word hilarious has now become apt to describe just about any situation in life.  Formerly this word was used only to describe something very, very funny.  Louis CK's resentments of this change are the comic stylings of his which I prefer.
summary: Very Good, Very Funny but not his show
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: Very crude, very funny, this comedy special. Most of the humor here pokes fun at familiar topics-- entitled people, flying, raising children, and his own quirks. It's not wickedly clever stuff, but amusing largely for Louis's sincerity and impressions. He's polished and relaxed for the duration. I'd probably be a bit uncomfortable having this on with my parents for the explicit imagery, but among friends? It's a riot.

The balance of the hour plus are not as funny and quite crude, he is definitely a funny guy but I will stick to seeing him during interviews and enjoying his "cleaner" deliveries.

reviewText: Very funny.  A little gross and disgusting at times, and lots of profanity, but it had me laughing hard a good deal of the time.Some reviewers have criticized him for the vulgarity and portrayed him as cheap, but I found that under the surface he was really thoughtful and had some interesting commentary about who we are as humans and as a species - really holding the mirror up to us.  I thought there were some real ethical undertones which I could relate to, and he did it in a really hilarious way (for some that is... for some it seems not to be their cup of tea).
summary: Funny... a little (lot) crude, but thoughtful.
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: Well, the man seems mildly gifted generally at comedy, but his material is dull and predictable.  I would say the content is only of interest to people living life from a level of consciousness that is highly nonexploratory, to put it mildly.  Otherwise I suspect you'll find this unrewarding and probably not finish watching it.  I ended up finishing it frankly only because I was not feeling motivated to go do anything else, but the effect was like watching a weakly written and directed sitcom re-run that is dated, cheesy and cliched. I also think he leans too long on barely passable material which wasn't all that funny to begin with, dragging it out until you are actually annoyed that he doesn't drop the bit and move on.

reviewText: I don't normally watch stand-up anymore, but I needed a break from all this heavy reading I've been doing.  I finally came out at the other end of the long, dark tunnel that is "Shantaram" (993 pages), then I dove into "Patanjali's Yoga Sutras" for extra torture (much shorter, but dense).  After putting myself through all that brain drain, noticing a comedian was available on Amazon Prime,  I jumped at him.Another thing I don't watch is cable TV.  I get the basic channels and that's more than enough.  So I knew nothing about this guy Louis C.K. (for Czekely, his Hungarian surname, although he bills himself as Mexican-American).  Apparently he's quite trendy, he has his own sitcom that was reviewed this week in "The New Yorker", he appears on all the right late-night shows, and he does a lot of these stand-up videos.C.K. has been compared to George Carlin, but after listening to him, I've gotta say, no way.  I'm old enough to remember Carlin's very first TV monologues.  He was always witty, topical, a student of word meanings, a gentle critic of society--a thinking, almost philosophical comic.  Granted, C.K. has carlinesque moments--like when he riffs on the over-the-top use of superlatives in everyday conversation, or when he talks about the word "Jew" meaning two different things depending on the context--but all the blue stuff, the scatology and pornography that appeals to 20-year-old males, is not.  Having said that, I'm sure Carlin had his own version of off-color humor that he took on the road, but what I saw was a "clean" comedian who detected irony and hypocrisy everywhere and reported back on it to the rest of us.So I don't know what to say about C.K.  He had me laughing, but he also had me gagging (the poop stuff got old fast, as did the gonado-centric humor).  And he wasn't consistent.  Near the beginning he said something like, life is crap and then you die and how he hates optimists, but later he talked about spoiled Americans complaining about insignificant problems like their cell phones not working right 100% of the time while people in other less developed countries have real problems to worry about.  He's from a different generation than mine, and that probably has something to do with not being totally enthralled with him.  So I'll give him three stars plus an extra star for his Hungarian DNA.
summary: Carlin he isn't, but C.K. has his moments
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: I usually like Louis CK on his show, which is a family rated show, but this is too X-Rated for me.  Please understand that I am NOT a prude - I can swear like the best of them - but his sexual slurs and disgusting profanities in this act are just gross for gross's sake... it doesn't accomplish anything. . . it certainly doesn't make it funnier. . . in fact,  he could tell the same jokes with out the potty-mouth and it would still be hysterical.  He really does touch on funny topics. Half of the show I liked.  But the toilet humor was a deal breaker.
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: Although the transmission was perfect as I've come to expect from Amazon, the quality of Louis C. K.'s standup left a lot to be desired. At moments he was indeed funny but all too frequently he glossed over his lack of humor with stark vulgarity that could have been toned down and would have presented better. Maybe that's more in line with the expectations of a generation X audience but I'm older than that. All in all it was average.
summary: Be sure you don't have your kids in the room.

reviewText: Here is the Bill Cosby of the 21st century. The Cos' spoke of stuff from his own personal experience, from childhood through growing up, having a job , raising a family, and dealing with life's stresses and rewards. While Cosby did so in a "G" rated manner, Louis C.K. does similar stuff in an off the boards "R" rated way. It fits the modern way of life, and to my ears it's not offensive, it's just the way the current generation gets its point across! I recommend this to anybody who won't be offended by the F-bomb being used...it's there, no way around it. But the DVD is great...just a stand-up routine taped before an audience...not as manic as early Robin Williams. The title says it all...Hilarious.
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious

reviewText: So much yuppie whining gets on my nerves. I could not relate to his jokes, though I see why many find him funny.I suspect almost all of his audience is like him, middle aged suburban yuppies. If that's you, you will find him funny. That's obvious by his audience and the very restrained middle class laughter you hear from them. Polite chuckles only.But I did not hear or see any unrestrained roaring gut busting laughter the whole program. Working class people, blue collar types, minorities, and non button downed types in general won't find him funny. We like to laugh out loud until we ache, not just chuckle.
Title: Louis C.K: Hilarious
